properties.Name: Canada
properties.Content: Canada received the highest number of non-fillet fresh fish exports from the U.S. by a significant margin every year from 2016-2021. Canada and the U.S. share one of the largest trading relationships in the world, in part due to close cultural ties, and in part due to the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA), which allows U.S. companies to ship qualifying goods to Canada or Mexico duty-free.

properties.Name: Japan
properties.Content: The U.S. and Japan recently signed the U.S.-Japan Trade Agreement, which entered into force on January 1, 2020.  The relationship is important to the U.S. given its geopolitical interests in East Asia, and a majority of Japanese citizens consider the U.S. to be their closest ally.

properties.Name: France
properties.Content: France was a significant importer of American non-fillet fresh fish in 2016, but has since reduced its imports significantly. France is part of the European Union, which is one of the U.S.�s largest and most important trading partners. properties.Name: Mexico
properties.Content: Mexico was the second largest importer of American non-fillet fresh fish in 2016, but has since decreased its imports. Mexico is one of the U.S.�s largest trading partners for goods overall, in part due to proximity, and in part due to the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA), which allows U.S. companies to ship qualifying goods to Canada or Mexico duty-free.

properties.Name: Nigeria
properties.Content: Nigeria went from a relatively small importer of U.S. non-fillet fresh fish in 2016 to the second largest behind Canada in 2021.  Non-fillet fresh fish was the only industry in the OEC dataset where Nigeria was one of the top importers.
